[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1812 Louisiana gubernatorial election** was the first gubernatorial election to take place after Louisiana achieved statehood.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] Under Article 3 Sec 2 of the 1812 Constitution of the State of Louisiana the Governor was elected in two steps.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] On the first Monday in July, eligible voters went to the polls and voted.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The returns were sent to the President of the Louisiana State Senate.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] On the second day of the session of the Louisiana State Legislature, the Louisiana House of Representatives and Senate met in joint session and voted between the top two candidates.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The candidate who received a majority in General Assembly became governor.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] The **1812–13 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 3, 1812, and April 30, 1813.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 13th United States Congress convened on May 24, 1813.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] They coincided with James Madison being re-elected president.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] With the addition of the new state of Louisiana's at-large seat, along with the 39-seat gain as a result of the congressional reapportionment based on the 1810 United States census, the size of the House increased to 182 seats.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Most relative population growth was in the West.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] After America's entry into the War of 1812 against Britain, the Democratic-Republican and Federalist parties maintained pro-war and anti-war positions, respectively.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Democratic-Republican representatives supported by voters in agrarian regions and Southern and Western states promoted war, asserting that Britain had violated American sovereignty and that despite Britain's strength, war was a manageable risk.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Federalists and their supporters in New England and more densely populated Eastern districts opposed the war, citing likely damage to American trade and infrastructure.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] This election saw significant voter support shift to the declining Federalists for the last time, almost entirely in New England, New York, and New Jersey.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Despite this shift, Federalists did not approach national political recovery, House control, or meaningful policy influence.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Following the 1810 census, the House was reapportioned, adding 39 new seats.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] There were special elections in 1812 and 1813 to the 12th United States Congress and 13th United States Congress.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Special elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Connecticut elected its members September 21, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Its apportionment was unchanged after the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Delaware gained a seat after the 1810 census, and chose to elect both seats on a general ticket.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] The ten years between 1813 and 1823 were the only time when Delaware was represented by more than one Representative, and is one of only three states (the other two being Alaska and Wyoming) that have never been divided into districts.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Delaware elected its members October 6, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Georgia gained two seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Georgia elected its members October 5, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Kentucky gained four seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Georgia elected its members August 3, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Louisiana held its election for the 13th Congress September 28–30, 1812, at the same time as the election for the 12th Congress, with nearly-identical results.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] It elected its members October 12, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Massachusetts gained three seats after the 1810 census, all of which were added to the District of Maine.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Its elections were held November 5, 1812, but since Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in the 19th district, a second ballot was held there January 6, 1813.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] New Hampshire gained one seat after the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Its elections were held August 31, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] New Jersey kept its delegation at six seats but changed from electing its Representatives on a statewide general ticket to using three plural districts of two seats each.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] These districts were used only for the 1812 election, and the state returned to using a single at-large district in 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] This was only the second time that New Jersey used districts (the first being in 1798).
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] *Tufts Digital Collations and Archives*.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] A New Nation Votes: American Election Returns 1787–1825.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Archived from the original on August 7, 2020.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Ten seats were added after the 1810 census, bringing New York's representation to 27, the largest of any state at the time.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] New York would remain the state with the most members until surpassed by California in the 1970 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] There were two separate House of Representatives elections in 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] The first was held in April 1812 for an un-reapportioned 17 representatives.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] This election was subsequently declared void and a new election was held on December 15–17, 1812, in which only three incumbents ran and two of whom were re-elected.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] New York thereby lost 4 Democratic-Republicans and gained 14 Federalists.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] North Carolina gained one representative as a result of the census of 1810.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Its elections were held April 30, 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] The 1810 census revealed dramatic population growth in Ohio since 1800, resulting in its representation increasing from a single Representative to six, resulting in the State being broken up into 6 districts, abolishing the at-large district.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Jeremiah Morrow (Democratic-Republican), who had served since Ohio achieved statehood in 1803, retired to run for U.S.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Senator, so that all six seats were open.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Its elections were held October 13, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] There was a special election in the 6th district, held due to the death of Representative-elect John S.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Pennsylvania gained five seats in the House of Representatives as a result of the census of 1810, which awarded it a total of 23 seats.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] Pennsylvania was re-districted into 15 districts, one with 4 seats, five with 2, and the remaining nine with 1 seat each.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p01] There were seven open seats for this election, five resulting from the increase in apportionment, and two resulting from the retirement of incumbents.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Rhode Island's apportionment was unchanged.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Its elections were held August 25, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1810 census, increasing from 8 seats to 9.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Its elections were held October 12–13, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Tennessee's representation increased from 3 seats to 6 as a result of the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Its elections were held April 1–2, 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Vermont gained two seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Rather than re-district, however, Vermont replaced its districts with a single at-large district.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] It would continue to use an at-large district in 1814, 1816, and 1818, then one more time in 1822 (with 5 seats).
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Its elections were held September 1, 1812.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Virginia gained one seat after the 1810 census, bringing its representation in the House of Representatives to 23 seats, the largest number Virginia would ever have.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Virginia went from having the most representatives to having the second-most tied with Pennsylvania.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] New York, with its 27 seats, surpassed Virginia and remained the most populous state until the late 1960s.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Its elections were held in April 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Four territories had delegates in the 13th Congress: Illinois, Indiana, Mississippi, and Missouri.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-louisiana-p02] Illinois Territory and Missouri Territory elected their delegates in 1812 for both the end of the 12th and the start of the 13th Congresses.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election-in-louisiana] The **1812 United States presidential election in Louisiana** took place between October 30 and December 2, 1812, as part of the 1812 United States presidential election.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election-in-louisiana] The state legislature chose three representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election-in-louisiana] Louisiana, which became the 18th state on April 30, 1812, cast its three electoral votes to Democratic Republican candidate and incumbent President James Madison in the state's first presidential election.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] The **1812–13 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President James Madison's re-election.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1812 and 1813, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] The Democratic-Republican Party lost two seats but still retained an overwhelming Senate majority.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] As in recent elections, the minority Federalists had gone into the elections with such a small share of Senate seats (6 out of 36, or 16.7%) that if they had won every one of the elections, they would still not have controlled a majority.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] Composition after September 1812 elections in the new state of Louisiana.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] In these special elections, the winners were seated during 1812 or before March 4, 1813; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1813 (except where noted due to late election); ordered by state.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] In these special elections, the winners were seated in 1813 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] The Maryland legislature failed to elect a senator before the March 3, 1813, the beginning of the term.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] Robert Henry Goldsborough was appointed to fill the seat.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1812-united-states-senate-elections-in-louisiana] Goldsborough won election over Edward Lloyd by a margin of 20.45%, or 18 votes, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] The **1814–15 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 26, 1814, and August 10, 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 14th United States Congress convened on December 4, 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] They occurred during President James Madison's second term.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Elections were held for all 182 seats, representing 18 states.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Though several were held after the conflict had ended, most elections took place towards the end of the War of 1812, which was extremely unpopular in certain regions, particularly New England.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] The failed American invasion of Upper Canada (Ontario) and the 1814 Burning of Washington were embarrassing military setbacks, but the Democratic-Republican Party remained dominant and the declining Federalist Party was unable to convert war opposition into political gain.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] This election marked the first in American history where the incumbent president's party gained House seats in a midterm election while still losing seats in the Senate; this happened again in 1822 and 1902.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] There were special elections in 1814 and 1815 to the 13th United States Congress and 14th United States Congress.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Connecticut held its election September 19, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Delaware held its election October 4, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Georgia held its election October 3, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Kentucky held its elections August 3, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Louisiana held its election July 4–6, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Maryland held its elections October 3, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Massachusetts held its elections November 7, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] State law required a majority vote for election which was not met in two districts, leading to a second election January 6, 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] District numbers differed between source used and elsewhere on Wikipedia; district numbers used elsewhere on Wikipedia used here.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] New Hampshire held its election August 29, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] New Jersey held its election October 10–11, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] The state returned to an at-large basis for electing its representatives, abolishing the short-lived districts of the previous election.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] New York held its elections April 26–28, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] North Carolina held its elections August 10, 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Ohio held its elections October 11, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Pennsylvania held its elections October 11, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] Rhode Island held its election August 30, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p01] South Carolina held its elections October 10–11, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] Tennessee held its elections August 3–4, 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] Vermont held its elections September 6, 1814.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] Voters swung from one party to the other.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] The margins were close, actually, but to toss the entire six-member delegation out of office.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] Virginia held its elections in April 1815.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] Four territories sent delegates to the 14th Congress.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1814-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-louisiana-p02] This was the last election for Indiana Territory, as it was admitted to the Union as a state in 1816.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Louisiana gubernatorial election** was the fifth gubernatorial election to take place after Louisiana achieved statehood.
[src:1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] Under Article III Sec 2 of the 1812 Constitution of the State of Louisiana the Governor was elected in two steps.
